Date: 0/0/1898
Source: Austral English
Author: MORRIS
Vol / Page: 411
Edition:
Quote: <i>Shanty, n</i>. (1) a hastily erected wooden house; (2) a public-house, especially unlicensed: a sly-grog shop. The word is by origin Keltic (Irish). In the first sense, its use is Canadian or American; in the last, Australian. In Barrere and Leland it is said that circus and showmen always call a public-house a shanty.
Notes:

